<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JAN 93 / International Company News: UTC cuts deficit to Dollars 333m
in final period
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNITED Technologies, which yesterday announced big job cuts at its Pratt &amp;
Whitney aero-engine business, also reported a fourth-quarter loss of Dollars
333m but said the full-year operating performances of all its businesses had
improved, with the exception of Pratt &amp; Whitney.
The fourth-quarter loss, the result of Dollars 701m of pre-tax charges,
worked through at Dollars 2.77 a share and compared with a loss of Dollars
1.22bn, or Dollars 10.33 a share, in the same period of 1991 when UTC took
restructuring and environmental charges totalling Dollars 1.53bn.
Fourth-quarter revenues were Dollars 5.755bn, against Dollars 5.808bn.
For 1992 as a whole, UTC reported a net loss of Dollars 287m, or Dollars
2.67 a share, after charges and accounting changes, compared with a loss of
Dollars 1.02bn, or Dollars 8.91 a share, for 1991.
Mr Robert Daniell, UTC's chairman, said Pratt &amp; Whitney's 1992 earnings
before charges and accounting changes declined to Dollars 320m from Dollars
502m the previous year, and Dollars 596m of the Dollars 701m fourth-quarter
charges applied to this business.
In the fourth quarter, excluding charges and accounting changes, Pratt &amp;
Whitney's operating income dropped to Dollars 28m from Dollars 138m, due to
lower commercial jet engine spare part sales and reduced engine shipments.
The flight systems business saw an increase in fourth-quarter operating
profit from Dollars 63m to Dollars 129m, thanks in part to an improved
operating performance at Sikorsky,the helicopter manufacturer.
Building systems saw operating income rise from Dollars 63m to Dollars 99m,
with air conditioning manufacturer Carrier enjoying a strong performance in
North America and Otis, the elevator business, achieving increased service
volume overseas.
The automotive components business had operating income of Dollars 29m,
against Dollars 23m.
