<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JAN 93 / Westminster council to reduce pensions of 600 ex-employees
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WESTMINSTER City Council is set to cut the pensions of 600 former employees,
giving them less than a month's notice, on the grounds that existing
payments are too generous under the law.
The pensioners will be deprived of an average of Pounds 750 a year, about 15
per cent of their pension. The only relief on offer is a welfare counselling
service.
One in six of Westminster's pensioners will be affected by the cuts, ranging
from former cleaning staff to senior council officers. They are virtually
all people made redundant at the age of 50 or above within the past five
years, mostly as a result of restructuring or competitive tendering of
services.
The cuts are expected to save the council's superannuation fund Pounds
450,000 a year.
On the basis of advice from leading QCs, Westminster believes that pensions
paid under the redundancy package it operated until last year are probably
too generous, because they exceed those prescribed by the 1972
Superannuation Act and subsequent regulations.
Westminster has already acted to curb the size of future lump sum and
pension payments. The decision to cut the pensions of those who left the
council before those changes will almost certainly be taken this Friday, at
a three-member sub-committee of Westminster's policy and resources
committee.
Letters will then be sent to those affected. No attempt will be made to claw
back sums already paid.
Mr Bill Roots, Westminster's finance director, said yesterday: 'This is an
awful business, but we have no choice in the matter. I have a clear duty to
follow legal advice that the current level of payments is unlawful.'
Westminster took advice after a Court of Appeal ruling in March 1992 that
North Tyneside council's voluntary severance scheme was unlawful because it
was more generous than that provided by government regulations. The level of
continuing pensions paid to those over 50 was not a direct issue, but may
have been affected.
The Audit Commission, the local government watchdog, has advised councils to
re-examine severance schemes. Swansea City Council last November reduced the
pensions of 110 former staff by an average of 10 per cent.
</TEXT>
