<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JAN 93 / Climbdown inevitable over pits as MPs agree rescue plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN EXPENSIVE government climbdown over the future of the coal industry
became inevitable last night after a cross-party committee of MPs agreed
plans which would safeguard at least half of the 31 pits threatened with
closure.
Ministers conceded that the proposals would form the benchmark for the white
paper on the industry promised by Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and
industry secretary, for early next month.
A report from the House of Commons trade and industry committee told the
government to increase the market for domestic coal in the generating
industry by a minimum of 16m tonnes a year at a cost of about Pounds 300m.
It suggested that a further 3m tonnes might be sold outside the electricity
industry.
Yesterday Mr Heseltine met senior cabinet colleagues to finalise a draft of
the white paper to be presented to Mr John Major, the prime minister, on his
return from India later this week. Any attempt by the government to propose
an overall market smaller than the minimum of 56m tonnes recommended by the
committee would invite a further damaging defeat in the House of Commons.
The MPs, who agreed the report after two days of wrangling between the
Labour and Tory groups on the committee, made no mention of the number of
pits which would be saved.
But privately they agreed that the plan would mean that 16 pits would be
assured of survival, with the future of three or four others in the balance.
The remainder might be kept open for a short period while they were stripped
of easily-accessible reserves.
Plan to save up to 19 pits, Page 11
