<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JAN 93 / SFO seeks to stop public hearings on Maxwell
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Serious Fraud Office has asked a Commons select committee to halt public
hearings into the theft of funds from the Maxwell company pension schemes
because many of those to be called are material witnesses in forthcoming
trials.
Among those scheduled to testify were Lord Walker, Lord Rippon and Lord
Stevens as well as officials of Lehman Brothers International, Capel-Cure
Myers and Bank of America.
Mr Frank Field, chairman of the select committee on social security,
yesterday called off the scheduled questioning of Mr Basil Brookes, former
Maxwell Communication Corporation finance director, after receiving a letter
on Monday from the SFO.
The SFO said MPs were likely to question witnesses about matters that the
SFO itself was pursuing in criminal proceedings. So far, Maxwell's sons
Kevin and Ian, Mr Larry Trachtenberg and Mr Robert Bunn have been charged in
connection with the theft of more than Pounds 440m from the pension schemes.
Members of the committee are to meet the SFO tomorrow to discuss how to
proceed.
Some select committee members privately expressed frustration with the
request, but said they would have little choice but to co-operate.
Several suggested that the SFO was concerned about damage to its own
reputation if court proceedings failed to produce convictions.
'We had always said we did not wish our proceedings to prejudice court
proceedings,' Mr Field said. MPs fear that those charged in connection with
the theft may try to claim that adverse pre-trial publicity prevented a fair
hearing.
Mr Field said he hoped the committee would be able to continue hearing
evidence in public without prejudicing proceedings.
Mr David Shaw, a Conservative committee member, said if evidence had to be
taken in private, then a review should be held of the sub judice rules on
how what is said in parliament affects court proceedings.
</TEXT>
