<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JAN 93 / Observer: Spark fired
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Instead of seeing British Airways heads rolling over the Virgin Atlantic
affair, we now have Richard Branson and BA's Sir Colin Marshall looking
forward to building a new, writ-free relationship on the back of this week's
kiss-and-make-up session at Branson's Holland Park home.
Even so, one innocent bystander has been forced to make the ultimate
sacrifice. He is Roland Spark, the Sun's chief leader writer for the last 14
years, and one of the crispest pontificators in the press.
His crime? Dissociating himself from some other author's Sun leader
attacking British Airways's dirty tricks. Spark, now 63, thinks BA's
75-year-old chairman Lord King has been 'kicked around long enough' and
wrote a letter of sympathy after a particularly vicious Sun attack. When Sun
editor Kelvin MacKenzie learned about it, he sacked him.
If only the BA board were as ruthless. But then they might not be allowed to
get away with it.
