<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JAN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Labour faces tough cash choices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR'S national executive must today grasp the nettle of falling
membership and income by voting on the deepest organisational cutbacks in
the party's 93-year history.
The retrenchment involves plans to curb expenditure and manpower by about a
third, leading to some 30 job losses out of its 120-strong Walworth Road
headquarters staff and the closure of up to five of the 11 regional offices.
Under plans submitted by Mr Larry Whitty, the party's general secretary, the
executive must attempt to find savings of some Pounds 4m a year from a
general fund budget of Pounds 12m.
Some NEC members are fighting hard to ensure that the regional cuts are
limited while others have battled to keep enough critical mass in the
Walworth Road policy research department to maintain a viable service to
local government, constituencies and unions.
Lobbying is believed to have ensured that some cuts in the policy department
have been reversed in a revised plan for Walworth Road due to be formally
submitted for debate by the general secretary today.
However, the overall impact of the proposed reforms will serve to bolster Mr
John Smith's efforts to integrate more closely the activities of the party's
headquarters with those of his own leader's office at Westminster.
That process has been continuing apace under Mr Smith's seven-month tenure
of the party leadership. It is further confirmed by his decision to
redesignate Mr David Hill, the campaigns and communications' chief, as
overall party spokesman.
The change will release Mr Hill to oversee an integrated media management
operation which encompasses servicing the interests of the leader, the
shadow cabinet, the parliamentary party and the NEC. That move is expected
to receive formal approval at today's meeting.
Similarly, with the squeeze on manpower now taking hold, more work is
expected to be handled by integrated NEC/shadow cabinet working groups,
thereby avoiding duplication of effort.
Some senior party figures and unions have expressed misgivings that the
traditional division of power between the NEC, representing the national
party, and the parliamentary party is being eroded.
Mr David Blunkett, the shadow health secretary and an NEC member, underlined
at a meeting in December that it was imperative local parties maintained
access to a source of data and research.
Furthermore, as a former leader of Sheffield council, Mr Blunkett has argued
strongly for Labour's local government conference to be exempt from a plan
to save money by putting most annual conferences on a biennial basis.
</TEXT>
