<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JAN 93 / Dilemma over dealing with City cases: Efforts to find a
solution to long, complicated trials
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE QUESTION of whether cases such as the Blue Arrow fraud trial should have
been dealt with by the criminal courts or by the City regulators was central
to the Bar working party's efforts to find a solution to the problems of
long fraud trials.
The Blue Arrow trial, which ended last February, lasted a year and four
days. Four men were convicted of conspiracy to defraud after the 1987 Pounds
873m failure of the Blue Arrow rights issue - the convictions were quashed
on appeal.
'Certainly the Stock Exchange felt at the time it could have dealt with it
more effectively and speedily. Hopefully Blue Arrow was a one-off,' says Mr
Jeremy Roberts QC, chairman of the working party.
Criminal offences involving fraud or financial irregularity embrace an
enormous range of degrees of culpability. At one extreme there are blatant
cases of dishonesty, which Mr Roberts says should always be dealt with by
the criminal courts.
At the other end of the scale are a variety of offences, many of a technical
nature, where the defendant has 'broken the rules', but neither desired nor
expected that anyone else would lose money.
The Bar believes there is a strong argument that many such offences would be
better dealt with in some other way than devoting a large amount of public
time and money to a criminal prosecution. The problem is how to decide which
cases can be left to City regulators and which cases must be dealt with by
the courts.
It suggests that the solution hinges on the likely penalty for the offence.
If there is a risk that the accused will be sent to prison if convicted, the
case should be dealt with by the courts. If the likely outcome is a fine, a
conditional discharge or some other non-custodial sentence, the case ought
normally to be dealt with by disciplinary proceedings. This risk should be
assessed in discussion between City regulators and the Serious Fraud Office.
Mr Roberts accepts that allowing City regulators to deal with City offences
may be perceived by the public as a 'soft option' for the accused. The
accusation might be levelled that 'shoplifters go to prison; white-collar
criminals don't'
But the Bar believes the penalties disciplinary tribunals can impose are
quite stringent. Infringement of City rules can result in financial
penalties, suspension or termination of membership of a professional or self
regulatory body and an order to compensate the victims of any financial
irregularity.
City disciplinary systems are also capable of reaching a much speedier
resolution. An examination of cases dealt with by the Securities and Futures
Association shows that in most cases the delay between the commencement of
an investigation and conclusion of the case is between two and four months.
It has taken seven years to reach the end of the prosecutions arising out of
the 1986 Guinness takeover of Distillers.
But the Bar accepts that, to reassure the public, steps will have to be
taken to make City disciplinary proceedings more transparent. While
plea-bargaining and disciplinary proceedings continue to be held in private,
it will be very difficult to ensure public confidence in them. The onus is
on the City to address this problem.
The Bar also recommends that the Serious Fraud Office and the Crown
Prosecution Service have the power to 'compound' - to agree, in suitable
cases, to accept a financial penalty as an alternative to bringing criminal
charges. The Inland Revenue and Customs and Excise currently have this
power.
In many cases, compounding might be the most effective way of obtaining
recompense for the victims of fraud, Mr Roberts says.
Recent lengthy financial trials include:
GUINNESS 1: three men were jailed and a fourth fined for offences of theft,
conspiracy to defraud and false accounting arising out of the 1986 Pounds
2.72bn Guinness takeover of Distillers. The trial lasted six months.
BRITANNIA THEME PARK: the UK's longest criminal trial started in September
1990 and ended in February 1992. Four men were jailed and a fifth was fined
over the 1985 collapse of the Britannia Theme Park at Shipley, Derbyshire,
with debts of Pounds 9.34m.
BARLOW CLOWES: almost a year ago Mr Peter Clowes was jailed for theft and
fraud after the Pounds 150m collapse of his investment company Barlow
Clowes. The trial lasted seven months.
BLUE ARROW: four men were convicted of conspiracy to defraud after the 1987
Pounds 873m failure of the Blue Arrow rights issue in a trial of a year and
four days. The convictions were quashed on appeal.
GUINNESS 2: the trial was abandoned last February after five months because
of the ill-health of one of the two defendants, former merchant banker Mr
Roger Seelig.
</TEXT>
<XX>
