<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JAN 93 / Accountancy rule adoption 'slow'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPANIES are proving slow to adopt the new accounting standard on profit
and loss accounts, according to Company Reporting, the Edinburgh-based
monthly monitoring service of annual reports.
Just six companies - 4 per cent of those issuing annual reports in the 11
weeks since FRS 3 standard was circulated in late October - have adopted its
guidance.
That compares with 16 companies, or 10 per cent, which adopted FRS 1, the
other principal accounting standard, in the same period after its
publication. FRS 1 was introduced in September 1991 and deals with cashflow.
Mr Iain Martin of Company Reporting said adoption might be slower because
'people are not so sure about whether it is a good thing'. He said FRS 1 was
welcomed as an improvement on the old source and application of funds
statement.
