<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JAN 93 / Insolvency body plan in dispute
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PLANS FOR a joint regulatory body for insolvency practitioners are being
held up by a dispute over its control.
The Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales, which regulates
nearly half of UK practitioners, wants more than a proposed three out of 11
voting shares on the Joint Insolvency Monitoring Unit.
Discussions are well advanced for the creation of the unit, which would be
supported by the principal professional insolvency bodies - the three UK
chartered accountancy institutes, the certified accountants and Institute of
Practitioners of Insolvency.
Plans for the unit, which would be registered as a limited company, were
generated by pressure from the Department of Trade and Industry. It believes
on the basis of random inspections last year that monitoring of
practitioners was not rigorous enough.
It would inspect all the UK's 2,000 insolvency practitioners every three to
five years.
Meanwhile the DTI is likely to hand to the Insolvency Practitioners'
Association control of the registration and supervision of about 150
individuals who fall outside the bodies recognised in the 1986 Insolvency
Act. The government's insolvency service, which is under financial pressure,
sees the move as a logical development of the self-regulatory regime.
</TEXT>
