<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JAN 93 / SIB is told to reduce demands on new unit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Securities and Invest-ments Board will have to soften its demands for
strengthening the planned Personal Investment Authority if it is to earn the
acceptance of the industry, Sir Gordon Downey, chairman of Fimbra, the
self-regulatory body for independent financial advisers, warned yesterday.
Sir Gordon, who is also chairman of the new authority's board, said he
broadly welcomed a recent letter from SIB's chairman, Mr Andrew Large,
stating that the authority would not be approved unless it delivered
significantly better investor protection.
However, several points raised by Mr Large would require negotiation, he
said. 'Whether we (the authority's board) can reach agreement is anybody's
guess. And even if the board members can agree among themselves, they will
still need the support of the 75 per cent majorities of Lautro (the
self-regulatory body for the life insurance industry) and Fimbra members.
This is no easy task.'
In particular, Sir Gordon questioned whether independent financial advisers
should, as Mr Large has said, be required to have Pounds 10,000 in capital
in order to be allowed to operate.
Fimbra members have objected to the requirement, and the industry trade
association estimates that such a rule could put 50 per cent to 60 per cent
of independent advisers out of business. Mr Ken Bignall, managing director
of Barclays Financial Services and a member of the authority's board, said
the new tougher standards proposed by Mr Large go a long way towards
satisfying some of his concerns about joining the body.
</TEXT>
