<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JAN 93 / Tourist authority chief quits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR William Davis, chairman of the British Tourist Authority and the English
Tourist Board, said yesterday he was leaving both jobs and attacked the
government for not doing enough to assist the tourist industry.
Mr Davis said he had told Mr Peter Brooke, the national heritage secretary,
that he did not want to continue in the two posts when his three-year term
of office ended on March 31. Mr Davis said he had not been offered another
three-year term and Mr Brooke did not try to dissuade him from leaving.
Mr Davis criticised the government for cutting the ETB's grant from Pounds
15.6m last year to Pounds 9.1m in 1995. 'The cuts in the ETB budget herald
the demise of the ETB,' he said.
Mr Davis, a former journalist, said he would devote more time to his
magazine publishing company.
The Department of National Heritage said yesterday Mr Davis's term was due
to end on March 31 and 'it is not normal practice to automatically extend
appointments. An announcement will be made soon about his successor.'
Mr Michael Medlicott, BTA chief executive, is also leaving the authority to
become European vice president of Delta Air Lines, the US carrier. He said
his departure was unrelated to that of Mr Davis.
Sir Colin Marshall, chief executive of British Airways, will also leave the
BTA board at the end of this month when his term ends. He said yesterday
that after seven years on the board it was time for fresh blood.
