<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JAN 93 / Record number of jobless seek mental help
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RECORD numbers of unemployed people are being referred by their doctors to
clinical psychologists, the British Psychological Society said yesterday.
The society said that in calculating the full costs of unemployment it was
essential to include the social costs of increased physical and mental
ill-health and the added reliance on the National Health Service and welfare
systems.
Dr Jenny Cozens, a lecturer at Leeds University and a clinical and
occupational psychologist, said that there was a two-year waiting list in
some areas to see a clinical psychologist.
She said there was an 'indisputable link' between unemployment and mental
stress. Psychologists in parts of the Midlands were being inundated with
requests for help because of the pit closure programmes.
Dr Dilys Davies, a clinical psychologist for North East Warwickshire Health
Authority, said the emotional impact of job loss on middle class men in
areas such as the south-east - worst hit by the recession - could be
devastating.
She said: 'They internalise it more than working class men and see it as a
personal failure. In working class communities where there is a history of
unemployment people do not take it as personally.'
Nevertheless she said unemployment was worse for poor people because
alternative work was more limited.
Mr Andrew Stephenson, aged 37, a security consultant who became unemployed
last August and a founder of Reaction, a self-help group in Sheffield, said:
'I felt isolated and I did not want to talk to my friends about it when I
lost my job.
'There was a lurking fear that because things change so quickly I would be
left behind if I did not get a job quickly. One does also deteriorate very
quickly if you just sit in front of the television.'
</TEXT>
