<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JAN 93 / Scotts water industry plans unpopular
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR IAN LANG, the Scottish secretary, is being urged to ignore widespread
opposition to the idea of privatising the water and sewerage industry in
Scotland and floating the industry as one or more companies on the Stock
Exchange.
Bell Lawrie White, the Edinburgh stockbroker, says the supposedly soft
option of franchising the management of the Scottish water industry to
private-sector companies would be just as unpopular as outright
privatisation, while being more complex and costly.
Political opposition to privatising the Scottish water industry has
intensified, with Strathclyde regional council saying it will put the
government's plans for the industry to a referendum of its 1.7m voters, once
they are finalised.
Bell Lawrie White was responding to a Scottish Office consultation paper
detailing options for the Scottish water and sewerage industries. Unlike
their counterparts in England and Wales, the Scottish industries are still
in the public sector.
The government says change is necessary because local government is being
reorganised and private-sector finance is desirable to help fund the
industry's heavy investment needs. Water privatisation in any form is
rejected not only by the opposition parties but by some Conservatives.
Recently the Scottish landowners' federation said it opposed the private
ownership of water.
Bell Lawrie White says creating one to three public limited companies
embracing the water industry and floating them on the Stock Exchange would
be seen by the public as a Scottish solution and would build on the
successful privatisation of the Scottish electricity companies.
The option of franchising water, under which the assets would be owned by a
new company limited by guarantee which franchised their operation to a
private company, would be unpopular because most potential franchisees would
be English or French rather than Scottish companies.
</TEXT>
