<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JAN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Lottery bill attacked by Labour
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT'S national lottery bill was 'the unacceptable face of
nationalisation', Labour said yesterday during Commons exchanges concerning
the bill's possible effects on employment in competing industries.
In the debate before the bill paving the way for the new lottery received
its second Commons reading, Ms Ann Clwyd, shadow heritage secretary, charged
the government with wrecking 'a perfectly reasonable proposition' through
its insensitivity.
Citing concern among MPs about the effects of a lottery on the football
pools industry, Ms Clwyd said the government had offered no safeguards as to
the future of a large number of private-sector jobs.
Labour preferred to put its faith in the established positions that the
pools industry provided rather than speculation about the number of jobs the
national lottery might create, she said. 'A job in the hand is worth more
than a job in the bush.'
Mr Peter Brooke, heritage secretary, said the bill would establish 'a new
multi-billion pound business' - an enterprise that would create around 1,000
'core' jobs in its central operation and many others in associated service
industries.
He confirmed reports that a confidential study commissioned by the
government had indicated the pools industry might lose 1,100 jobs
attributable to the lottery under certain circumstances, but said this
conclusion assumed pools companies did nothing to change the management of
their operations in response.
In fact, the pools sector had already responded to the potential threat
which the lottery poses.
'The pools are well able to adapt to change in order to preserve their own
interests.'
In an attempt to dispel Labour fears that the funds distributed by the
lottery might in effect act as a substitute for public spending, Mr Brooke
promised that proceeds would not be brought within the government control
total.
This point was underlined by Mr David Mellor, former heritage secretary, who
spoke of the need for it to be clear the government was not trying to
'slough off' responsibility for arts, sport and heritage.
Mr Mellor said that the only basis on which he could commend to the many
bodies that wanted the lottery that it would be a good thing was if the
undertaking not to use it as a substitute for public funds was 'honoured to
the letter'.
He said: 'The national lottery is only worth something if it is a quantum
leap forward for these interests. Otherwise I do not think we want it'.
Unlawful participation in foreign lotteries meant that the choice at issue
was not between one lottery or none 'but between benefit from the lottery in
the UK and benefit abroad,' Mr Brooke said.
A Labour amendment describing the bill as unacceptable in the form proposed
was defeated by 310 votes to 269, a government majority of 41.
The bill then received a second reading by 339-203, a government majority of
136, with Labour MPs being given a free vote.
</TEXT>
