<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JAN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Shipping lobby renews tax relief
campaign
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE cross-party campaign urging tax breaks for Britain's shipping industry
has been renewed in the run-up to the Budget.
An all-party Commons motion, launched by the Ulster Unionists and signed by
33 MPs so far, calls for the establishment of a maritime enterprise zone and
reiterates the industry's call for 100 per cent capital allowances and
relief for employers on income tax or national insurance contributions on
seafarers' earnings.
Signatories include Mr David Shaw, the Tory MP for Dover, and Sir Rhodes
Boyson, a member of the executive of the 1922 Tory backbench committee.
The last serious attempt to win tax concessions for the industry came in the
1991 budget process when more than 100 Tory MPs supported the proposals.
Although campaigners believe that 30 Tory MPs is a more realistic target
this time, as the suggestions put forward are more specific, the
government's overall Commons majority of just 21 MPs means that even about a
dozen Tories determined to pursue the matter could cause difficulties.
Tory MPs with an interest in shipping are already raising the issue in their
individual pre-Budget discussions with Treasury ministers. After a meeting
next week between representatives from the Chamber of Shipping, the
industry's trade association, and Mr Stephen Dorrell, the financial
secretary, the MPs will consider whether to make representations directly to
the prime minister.
Campaigners have been cheered by the fact that Mr Norman Lamont, the
chancellor, has asked for details of their complaint of unfair competition
in European shipping, with other EC countries giving greater incentives.
The industry believes its cause is helped by the position being starker than
before, and warns that unless help is given there will be no British-flagged
ships by the next election.
</TEXT>
