<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JAN 93 / Parliament and Politics: A passion for trains that could
derail BR policy - Philip Stephens profiles Tory backbencher Robert Adley
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ONE CABINET minister describes him as 'quite simply barmy'. A colleague on
the Tory backbenches says the problem is that he never outgrew a boyhood
passion for train sets.
But amid growing concern on the Tory backbenches about privatisation of
British Rail, those less-than-flattering judgments of Mr Robert Adley, the
MP for Christchurch, may disguise a more awkward truth for the government.
Mr Adley, a self-confessed railway fanatic turned Tory chairman of the
influential Commons backbench transport committee, has emerged as one of the
sharpest - and most dangerous - critics of thegovernment's BR strategy.
Last week his all-party committee produced a damning, if carefully coded,
assessment of the Department of Transport's plans to sell off BR's freight
business and to inject private sector competition into passenger services.
A still-sharper attack is promised during the lengthy Commons debate on the
privatisation bill published by Mr John MacGregor, the transport secretary.
If things go to plan Mr Adley will wage a guerrilla war against Mr MacGregor
as the bill winds its way through parliament during the next six months.
It is possible, just possible, that he will recruit another dozen or so
Conservative colleagues to his cause.
If he does, the government will be forced yet again to take its proposals
for privatisation back to the drawing board.
It is hard to deny that Mr Adley has eclectic tastes. During 20 years in the
House of Commons his political causes have ranged from passionate support
for the communist Chinese in their disputes with Vietnam to ardent, and
early, support for the ANC in South Africa.
An author of nine books on the age of steam railways who once filled his
garden with rail signalling equipment might also be said to be obsessive
about the cause of the railways. But if his hostility to the government's
plans for BR is founded on the assumption that rail is a superior form of
travel there is more to his case than mere nostalgia.
Mr Adley foresees another damaging episode in the post-war decline of rail
travel. In the process the government will alienate millions of natural
supporters - commuters and the users of rural BR lines - in the next general
election. It was Mr Adley who coined the phrase that the government's plans
would lead to 'a poll tax on wheels'.
He is relaxed about being branded an eccentric: 'I take it as quite a
compliment that I am being vilified. When ministers resort to personal
attacks it is a sure sign they are skating on thin ice.'
He is similarly dismissive about Mr MacGregor's claim that the government's
proposals have the overwhelming support of the Tory benches: 'When ministers
insist they have 100 per cent support it is usually because they haven't'
Mr Adley insists that he is not against competition - or privatisation. He
suggests that the government should scrap the 1947 act on which BR's
monopoly is based and establish a Rail Ombudsman to oversee fair competition
between BR and private-sector companies: 'What I want is a better railway'.
But the starting point should be a fundamental re-assessment of all forms of
transport and include a realistic judgment of the true costs of roads. Rail
subsidies are deemed bad but the economic, social and environmental costs of
the roads are ignored: 'The real problem is that we do not have a transport
policy in this country.'
Mr Adley is adamant that Mr MacGregor's plans for BR - selling off the
freight division, creating a new track authority and offering operating
franchises on individual lines - will not work.
Thus far the government has been unimpressed. But there is a niggling
suspicion at Westminster that Mr Adley may yet turn out to be one of those
mavericks with more than a fair share of common sense.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P4011  Railroads, Line-Haul Operating.
    P9621  Regulation, Administration of Transportation.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment and Analysis.
    PEOP  Personnel News.
</TP>
<XX>
People:-
</XX>
<PE>Adley, R MP for Christchurch (UK).
</PE>
