<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JAN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Renewed doubts over economy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A FEEBLE rise in bank and building society lending last month suggests that
the lowest base rates for 16 years have done little to entice people and
companies to borrow more.
Weak M4 lending, and the prospect of further heavy job cuts in the
construction industry, yesterday cast new doubt on the strength of the
economy.
But reports of improved optimism among businesses, further signs of a slight
upturn in the housing market and buoyant growth of cash and notes in
circulation indicated that some sort of recovery may be under way.
Yesterday's mixed signals on the UK economy will not make it any easier for
Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, to decide whether to cut base rates below
7 per cent ahead of the Budget on March 16.
Bank of England figures showed that M4 lending rose by Pounds 200m last
month, an improvement on the November figure when lending fell by Pounds
600m, but significantly less than economists' expectations.
The annual growth rate of M4 - notes and coins in circulation plus bank and
building society deposits - was similarly sluggish. It hit a record low and
dropped through the bottom limit of the government's recently announced
monitor range of 4-8 per cent.
M4 fell a seasonally adjusted 0.1 per cent on the month, to rise by 3.7 per
cent in the year to December. This compares with 4.6 per cent in the year to
November.
By contrast narrow money, which comprises mainly notes and coins in
circulation, rose by 0.2 per cent in December, taking the
seasonally-adjusted annual growth to 3 per cent.
Weekly figures for notes and coins in circulation indicate that the buoyancy
of M0 has continued this month with some economists estimating that the
annual rate for January will exceed 4 per cent.
Mr Michael Saunders, an economist at Salomon Brothers, the US investment
bank, said the discrepancy between the two sets of figures could be
explained by debt overhang.
The Treasury said two special factors had depressed the growth of M4 last
month; the purchase of debt by the government from British
Telecommunications and the electricity holding companies, and the switch by
big companies to monthly payments of value added tax.
Figures from the British Bankers Association yesterday confirmed the
sluggish nature of private and corporate sector lending. Total sterling
lending by the nine biggest UK banking groups to the UK private sector fell
by more than Pounds 1.7bn in December, the second fall in four months.
</TEXT>
