<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JAN 93 / The Economy: Builders set to lose 50,000 jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A FURTHER 50,000 jobs are expected to be shed by the construction industry
this year, taking the total to 500,000 since 1989, according to a survey
published yesterday.
Sir Brian Hill, president of the Building Employers Confederation, said the
industry had lost the equivalent of almost 600 jobs every working day since
summer 1989.
The confederation questioned more than 500 building companies about the
outlook for output and employment during the next 12 months. Just under half
of those questioned said they expected to announce more job losses by the
end of March.
Almost a fifth of companies reported that they were working at less than
half capacity. Two thirds said they had enough work to last only six months.
Sir Brian said the findings of the confederation's latest quarterly workload
survey showed that the industry remained in deep recession in spite of a few
brighter signs.
These included a rise in the number of visitors to houses for sale, and more
than a quarter of companies recording an increase in inquiries for work from
potential customers against 21 per cent reporting a fall. This is the first
positive balance since the second quarter of 1989.
The rise in inquiries and visitors still had to be translated into sales,
however. As a result the industry was forecasting a further fall in output
of 2 per cent this year, following declines of 6 per cent last year and 9
per cent in 1991.
'Whatever is happening in other sectors of industry it is clear from these
results that construction remains in serious recession,' Sir Brian said.
'The key indicators of output and employment are still pointing firmly
downwards and we have to face the appalling prospect that the construction
jobless total will reach the half-a-million mark during 1993.'
This would mean a 30 per cent cut in the industry's labour force since
summer 1989. More than 20,000 construction companies had failed since then,
half of them in the past 12 months.
The confederation appealed to the chancellor to help construction by cutting
interest rates further, reducing value added tax for house improvements, and
abolishing stamp duty in the March Budget.
It also wants the government to extend the period for which it will allow 20
per cent capital allowances on industrial and agricultural buildings ordered
before October 31 this year.
Sir Brian said the industry was enduring the worst recession in living
memory: 'Assuming we have confidence returning, then by the end of 1993, and
one hopes in 1994, construction will show recovery.'
</TEXT>
