<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JAN 93 / Classic FM set to silence sceptics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LATER this week Classic FM is expected to show that broadcasting 'the
world's most beautiful music' has the makings of a beautiful little
business.
Rajar, the new joint radio industry research body, will announce on Friday
its first findings and is expected to show that Classic, the UK's first
national commercial station, has attracted more than 4m listeners a week.
Classic said before its launch on September 7 that it would reach 2.8m
listeners a week.
In spite of the depth of the advertising recession, Classic has already
either taken or booked revenues of about Pounds 3.5m in advertising and
sponsorship - more than some people forecast it would earn in a year.
In the early weeks the advertisments came mainly from the music industry.
Now they have broadened to include financial services, travel and cars -
reflecting the fact that 60 per cent of the station's audience comes from
the ABC1 marketing categories.
Capital costs were Pounds 6.3m with running costs about Pounds 7m a year.
Breakeven seems very likely next year and has not been totally ruled out
this year.
When Mr John Spearman, former chairman of advertising agency Collet
Dickenson Pearce, sounded out friends in the media about whether he should
accept an offer to run Classic FM, the advice was unanimous. He was told:
'Don't touch it with a barge pole.'
The consensus was that a commercial radio station devoted to classical music
could not possibly work in the UK and might never get on air.
The apparent size of the challenge, combined with the commitment of
shareholders such as Time Warner, the world's largest media group,
Associated Newspapers, and GWR, the commercial radio group, persuaded Mr
Spearman to become chief executive.
Purists have sniffed at the occasional mispronunciation of a composer's
name. But Mr Spearman is likely to have the last laugh. 'We are a serious
national ABC1 medium. We will be quite difficult for advertisers to
overlook,' he says.
</TEXT>
