<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JAN 93 / PSA privatisation reaches the final stage
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government yesterday launched the final stage of the privatisation of
the Property Services Agency. It announced the sale of PSA's five building
management businesses, which conduct most of the maintenance and upkeep of
government buildings.
The five businesses, based in Edinburgh, Manchester, Leeds, Bristol and
London, employ 9,000 people and should have a combined fee income of Pounds
311m in this financial year.
The announcement comes two months after the controversial sale of the
agency's projects division to Tarmac, which will cost the government up to
Pounds 90m to cover liabilities and redundancy costs.
Coopers &amp; Lybrand, the accountancy firm advising the government, said the
management businesses were considerably healthier than the project division.
Mr Andrew Jordan, a partner, said he believed that the prices commanded by
the businesses would more than offset the redundancy costs the government
had agreed to pay.
The businesses are all in profit. For the past 15 months they have been
under the temporary management of Bovis which aimed to improve their
efficiency, systems and customer relations. Mr Jordan said: 'They are
remarkably good given they are government departments. They are surprisingly
commercial.'
The businesses have lost contracts over the past few years following the
decision to allow the private sector to compete for government business.
Coopers &amp; Lybrand said the companies expected to make up for the lost
business over the next five years by competing actively for new work.
The sale, to be conducted by competitive tender, will be advertised
throughout the European Community. Mr John Redwood, environment minister,
said he would prefer to sell each of the five businesses to a different
buyer, although bids for more than one business would be allowed.
Coopers &amp; Lybrand said it had received interest from more than 70
businesses, including contractors, consultants, utilities and building
management companies. Preliminary bids will be submitted by March 9, after
which final offers will be invited from shortlisted bidders.
The guidelines for the sale provide that the deal should look after the
interests of clients, taxpayers and staff. Coopers &amp; Lybrand said it would
try to sell to a buyer able to provide the maximum number of jobs and one
with sufficient financial strength to honour redundancy obligations. The
government will guarantee redundancy payments in the event of the buyer
going bankrupt in the next five years.
After the sale of the building management businesses, the sole remaining
part of the PSA in the Department of the Environment will be Property
Holdings.
</TEXT>
<XX>
