<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JAN 93 / Warning over lack of cover for exporters
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID DODWELL, World Trade Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EXPORTERS will suffer a 'substantial competitive disadvantage' unless the
government rejoins other European states in providing exporters with
reinsurance against political risks, such as coups, warns Trade Indemnity,
the UK credit insurance group.
In a report to the Department of Trade and Industry, published esterday,
Trade Indemnity calls on the government to work in partnership with private
insurers to provide reinsurance cover at commercial rates.
It calls for this cover to be extended to all private-sector insurers able
to work in the field - a criticism of the competitive advantage of NCM
Credit Insurance, its main UK competitor.
As part of a privatisation deal two years ago NCM was granted transitional
access to reinsurance cover in spite of the government's withdrawal from
short-term export credit insurance.
NCM's transitional support is due to run out at the end of next year. Mr
Colin Foxall, NCM's managing director, has called for the facility to be
made permanent.
The Trade Indemnity report complains that the UK is the only leading
industrial nation not providing state-backed insurance or reinsurance for
short-term credit risks, which account for 90 per cent of UK exports. As a
result UK exporters are likely to face difficulties in getting political
risk cover when the NCM transitional support ends.
The report challenges government hopes that private sector reinsurers would
emerge to fill the vacuum formed by its withdrawal from reinsurance
activity.
Even without the recession and a string of natural disasters that have
brought two bad years for reinsurers, it argues that the private sector
would lack capacity.
The report says leading reinsurers, including Swiss Re and Munich Re, are
'adamant' that no further capacity can be provided. It adds: 'Even Lloyd's
is flagging drastic reductions in available capacity. Insurance of 90 per
cent of the UK's exports now hinges on the balance sheet strength of TI and
NCM and their respective reinsurers.'
Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, yesterday launched a
Business in Europe campaign aimed at alerting companies to export
opportunities in the single market and providing streamlined help. This will
include the secondment from the private sector of 20 executives.
</TEXT>
