<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JAN 93 / Rifkind challenged over Trident
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR MALCOLM RIFKIND, the defence secretary, is being challenged to explain
why his ministry is considering proposals that were previously rejected as
unacceptable for refitting Trident submarines.
The Scottish Council Development and Industry said Mr Rifkind must explain
why lower standards of nuclear safety in refitting Trident may now be
acceptable.
The body, which lobbies for economic development in Scotland, also wants to
know why the matter is being decided before consulting the Nuclear
Installations Inspectorate.
The government will decide in the next few weeks whether work on refitting
Trident should be carried out at Rosyth, Fife, as was decided in 1986, or at
Devonport in Plymouth.
The Babcock Thorn consortium which manages Rosyth fears that if it loses the
Trident contract the yard, which employs 4,200 people, would close within a
few years.
The contest appears to be between a proposal by Devonport to convert
existing docks into a Trident refitting facility at a cost of Pounds 130m
and a similar project at Rosyth which would cost Pounds 147m.
A total of Pounds 120m has already been spent at Rosyth on building a brand
new facility to refit Trident. But in December Babcock Thorn submitted a
proposal based instead on refurbishing battleship docks, which the company
believes is being considered by the MoD on an equal footing with Devonport's
scheme. Babcock Thorn says that when it suggested a refurbishment scheme in
1991 the plan was rejected by the Ministry of Defence in favour of the
Pounds 267m new-build project.
The development body said: 'Either the original specification had
unnecessarily high requirements, or increased risks to safety and
operational efficiency are now being accepted as cost savings.' It said the
government should explain why lower safety standards may be accepted,
especially for Devonport where many more people live in the nuclear
emergency evacuation zone than at Rosyth.
'It cannot be wise for government to depart from its original specification
for a nuclear installation without a full explanation,' the development body
added.
Babcock Thorn had earlier feared that it was not being given a fair hearing
and that Mr Rifkind had already recommended in favour of Devonport's
proposal.
A decision on the issue is not expected before next week at the earliest.
</TEXT>
