<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JAN 93 / Dispute looms on bank watchdog
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BRITISH Bankers' Association said yesterday that it still had severe
doubts about the wisdom of extending the banking ombudsman scheme so that
incorporated businesses can complain to the ombudsman about banking
mistakes.
Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, is expected to announce in the next day or
two that Mr Laurence Shurman, the ombudsman, should be allowed to adjudicate
on complaints from small businesses. At the moment only unincorporated
businesses and individuals can use the scheme.
A dispute between the banks and the chancellor is likely over which
incorporated businesses should be allowed to use the scheme. The
government's intention is to provide a complaints mechanism to small
businesses, but finding a definition of a small business acceptable to the
banks is proving difficult.
The reform to the ombudsman scheme will be part of a package of measures
aimed at forcing banks to improve their services to small businesses,
following widespread complaints that banks are treating these customers
insensitively.
The ombudsman scheme can only adjudicate on banking errors. Mr Lamont is
therefore likely to urge the banks to improve their internal procedures for
handling complaints from customers of unfair treatment by appointing
internal ombudsmen. These would be able to examine the most common form of
complaint from small-business customers, that banks have unfairly changed
the terms and conditions of a loan or other bank ser-vice.
Mr Lamont is likely to clear the banks of levying excessive interest rates
on small-business loans, although he may question whether bank charges are
being increased too much in some cases.
</TEXT>
