<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JAN 93 / Clash over SIB proposals for new regulatory body
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A ROW has broken out between UK banks and the Securities and Investments
Board, regulator of the financial services industry, over SIB's recent
suggestion that it may need to acquire new powers to force individual
financial organisations to join specific self-regulatory organisations.
SIB has said that if banks continue to refuse to join a proposed new SRO for
the retail financial services industry, called the Personal Investment
Authority, it may need to ask the government for powers to 'define the scope
of SROs', or decide the membership of each SRO.
These powers would enable it to force the banks to join the PIA.
However, in a letter to SIB, the British Bankers' Association, the banks'
trade association, argues that giving such powers to SIB would mean 'the end
of the SROs in their present form'.
The letter continues: 'The SIB would ultimately find itself as the sole
authority, with the SRO boards evolv-ing into advisory boards relating to
divisions of the SIB.'
However, SIB is understood to be unimpressed by this argument that the
nature of the UK regulatory system would change radically. It feels the
banks have failed to provide any evidence for this view.
The banks are also likely to be disappointed in their interpretation of
recent remarks by Mr Anthony Nelson, the Treasury minister responsible for
financial services regulation.
They interpreted remarks he made last week as ruling out new primary
legislation for the reform of financial services regulation and that,
therefore, he would not be giving powers to SIB to define SROs' scope.
It is believed, however, that he is prepared to contemplate legislation if
the banks will not join the PIA of their own accord.
Earlier this month the banks' concerns about joining the PIA were eased
slightly when Mr Andrew Large, SIB chairman, told the PIA that its
regulatory standards must be tougher than it had originally been planning.
</TEXT>
