<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JAN 93 / EC may ban tankers from some coast areas
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER and AP
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
EC TRANSPORT and environ -ment ministers were last night examining the
possibility of excluding oil tankers from waters near environmentally
sensitive areas, following tanker disasters off the Shetland Islands and
north-west Spain, writes David Gardner in Brussels.
No decisions were expected from yesterday's unscheduled meeting, which was
called, EC diplomats acknowledged, to demonstrate politically that the
Community intends to act.
Transport ministers are to examine a forthcoming report on maritime safety
by the European Commission at their meeting in March, and expect to agree on
priority measures in June, according to Mr John MacGregor, the UK transport
secretary. One possibility is for the EC to draw up a mandatory new routing
system for vessels, to keep them away from vulnerable marine life areas.
Shell International Petroleum said yesterday that about 20 per cent of the
world's tankers were substandard and should be forced out of business, AP
reports from London. The ensuing rise in freight rates would allow
shipowners to replace ageing vessels with newer ones.
