<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JAN 93 / Danish foreign minister makes Maastricht pledge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HILARY BARNES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   COPENHAGEN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Niels Helveg Petersen, who took over as foreign minister in Denmark's
four-party coalition government yesterday, said his top priority would be to
secure a Yes vote for the Maastricht treaty on European union in the second
Danish referendum, to be held later this year.
'I regard it as my foremost task to achieve a Yes in the referendum and to
ensure that the Danish presidency of the European Council is carried out
satisfactorily,' he said yesterday.
'We shall make every effort to see that the presidency, which has been well
prepared, goes well.'
Mr Petersen, 54, is the most senior cabinet appointee from the Radical
Liberals, one of the small centre parties in the new government coalition.
He will play a key role in the European Community in coming months during
the six-month EC presidency which Denmark assumed at the beginning of the
year.
He succeeds former foreign minister and Euro-enthusiast, Mr Uffe
Ellemann-Jensen. The new cabinet was announced yesterday by Mr Poul Nyrup
Rasmussen, the new prime minister and chairman of the Social Democratic
party (SDP).
Mr Petersen said the new government had not set a date for the referendum
but he thought a date 'before June' was probable.
Mr Petersen's Radical Liberal party has a record of being sceptical towards
European integration, but the foreign minister said that he had advocated a
Yes to the Maastricht treaty in last year's referendum. He said he did not
think his European credentials could be doubted.
The new cabinet is the largest in Denmark's history with 24 members. Several
ministries have been split up to create enough portfolios to meet the
requirements of the coalition of the SDP, the Radicals, the Centre Democrats
and the Christian People's party. SDP politicians given key posts included
Mr Mogens Lykketoft, minister of finance, and Mr Hans Haekkerup, minister of
defence. Mr Jann Sjursen, Christian party, becomes the youngest cabinet
minister, at 29, taking the energy ministry.
</TEXT>
