<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JAN 93 / Accidents at work 'cost up to Pounds 15bn'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WORKPLACE accidents and ill-health cost Britain Pounds 10bn-Pounds 15bn a
year, with employers bearing Pounds 4bn-Pounds 9bn of the expense, according
to an investigation due to be published by the Health and Safety Executive.
Employers appear to be seriously underestimating the true cost of accidents
and wrongly assume that they will be fully covered by insurance, Mr John
Rimington, HSE director-general, said yesterday.
'Boards of directors need to take full and proper account of what these
events are actually costing them,' he said.
The estimates are the first attempt to put a realistic price tag on
occupational injuries and ill-health since the discovery in 1991 that
official figures were seriously flawed.
A survey of 40,000 households revealed then that more than two-thirds of
workplace accidents remained unreported in breach of the law - a far higher
proportion than previously thought.
The latest study, to be published in full in May, calculates the costs to
society of occupational accidents and illness. The estimates include social
security and National Health Service expenses, as well as financial and
other losses suffered by victims. The total cost is equivalent to 1.75-2.75
per cent of gross domestic product, the HSE said.
About 1.6m accidents resulting in injury are estimated to occur each year
and about 750,000 workers suffer occupational ill-health which results in
time off work.
For employers, costs of accidents and ill-health include Pounds 750m paid in
employers' liability insurance to cover compensation to injured workers, the
cost of recruiting and training replacements for those forced to give up
work and the cost of property loss. Employers' expenses equalled 5-10 per
cent of gross trading profits, the HSE estimated.
Detailed case studies of five organisations showed that companies' uninsured
costs could be between eight and 36 times greater than the costs of
insurance premiums.
This is substantially greater than the ratio of 4:1 which is commonly used
by industrial safety experts to estimate the total costs of accidents within
individual organisations.
Typically, companies pay for employers', product and public liability
insurance, but fail to calculate fully the costs arising from accidents of
production delays, fines, legal fees and management and clerical time taken
up by investigations.
Mr Rimington said the HSE had been surprised by the results of the case
studies. The Costs of Accidents at Work. Health and Safety Executive.
Stationery Office. Pounds 8.50
</TEXT>
