<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JAN 93 / Observer: Returns
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Still on the subject of contra cyclical stock-market indicators, Observer
has noticed another worrying sign. City stockbrokers who retired to run
small breweries in the country are starting to re-emerge in the City
Graham Axford, one-time corporate finance chief at James Capel, last month
gave up the chairmanship of the tiny Wiltshire brewery - makers of Old
Grumble - to return as head of corporate finance at Credit Lyonnais Laing.
Now Observer hears that John Dunsmore, once the City's number one brewing
analyst, is giving up his directorship of Midland's brewer Marstons, so that
he can rejoin NatWest Securities as head of equities. Hard to believe that
overcapacity in brewing is worse than in stockbroking. But whatever the
reason, Dunsmore's return is another sign of the rehabilitation of NatWest's
once troubled broking business.
</TEXT>
<XX>
