<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JAN 93 / Letter: Windfall tax would not help unemployment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr COLIN SKELLETT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, The proposal by the Labour party that utilities should 'pay a public
dividend (windfall tax) as a result of their excess profits' (Parliament and
Politics, January 20) to help generate jobs shows a basic misunderstanding
of the finances of the water industry.
More than 70 per cent of Wessex Water's profits are used to help fund new
capital investment programmes. Our total expenditure each year exceeds our
income by a considerable margin. Every day Wessex Water spends around Pounds
300,000 on new capital schemes to meet legally required higher standards and
to put right neglect of the past. This expenditure generates thousands of
jobs.
While wholeheartedly supporting the desire to reduce unemployment, as far as
the water industry is concerned, the Labour party's proposals would have the
opposite effect.
Colin Skellett,
managing director,
Wessex Water,
Wessex House,
Passage Street,
Bristol BS2 0JQ
