FT  26 JAN 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The most controversial programme of the evening is certainly Viewpoint 93
(ITV, 10.40) which investigates serial killers. Producer Mike Morley was
given easy access in the US and interviewed Bob Berdella, who tortured and
killed six men in Kansas, and filmed the case records of the 'Rostov
Ripper', responsible for over 50 murders in Russia. In the UK the Home
Office permitted an interview with Dennis Nilsen, who lured young men back
to his Muswell Hill flat for tea and strangulation, but then refused
permission for the footage to be screened.
For Love or Money (Channel 4, 9.00) is the first programme to cover the art
market in depth, and the fact that it does so in a jokey, ironic, style adds
to its appeal. Three incredibly successful and popular art films clutter the
schedule tonight. BBC 1 celebrates 25 years of Omnibus at 10.20 with another
screening of Ken Russell's celebration of the life and music of Frederick
Delius. This is followed by the uncut version of Don't Look Now, the
ultimate Venetian ghost story. Channel 4 hits back with the Merchant-Ivory
adaptation of EM Forster's Florentine idyll, A Room with a View. (10.00).
