<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JAN 93 / International Company News: Lines open for BT link with GM -
Martin Dickson and Paul Taylor examine suggestions that the UK company may
be about to take a stake in Electronic Date Systems
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON and PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES in Electronic Data Systems, the computer services subsidiary of
General Motors, rose sharply yesterday morning amid market speculation that
British Telecom might be discussing buying a stake in the business.
Both companies declined to comment on 'speculation and market rumours',
which originated last Saturday with a report in the Dallas Morning News that
British Telecom might take a 25 per cent stake in EDS. The American company,
which is based in Dallas, has a market capitalisation of nearly Dollars
17bn.
However, analysts detected signs that the two companies may have at least
been discussing some form of co-operation and shares in General Motors'
Class E stock, whose value is tied to EDS's performance, rose Dollars 1 3/8
to close at Dollars 35 3/8 yesterday. On Friday it rose Dollars 2 1/4 to
Dollars 34.
The class E stock was first issued by General Motors when it acquired EDS in
1984 from the company's founder, Mr Ross Perot, who severed his relations
with both businesses in 1986 after repeated disputes with GM's management.
GM still owns some 40 per cent of the stock.
Class E shareholders have no direct, legal right to EDS's assets, which are
controlled by GM, but dividends paid on the stock are based on EDS's
performance.
Some form of tie-up between BT and EDS could benefit both sides as
telecommunications and computer services industries increasingly overlap,
but it would also raise fresh questions about British Telecom's patchy
record of business forays in North America.
Since privatisation in 1984 BT has made a series of expensive investments in
the North American market as part of its international strategy, but these
have not proved particularly successful.
In November, BT agreed to sell its three-year-old minority stake in McCaw
Cellular Communications, the US mobile phone group, to American Telephone &amp;
Telegraph. The sale will be worth Dollars 49-a-share, or about Dollars
1.8bn, when it is completed later this year and has been widely perceived as
saving shareholders from an expensive error.
The same month BT recorded a sharp drop in its half-year pre-tax earnings,
mainly because of exceptional charges to cover the sale of its interest in
Mitel Corporation, the troubled Canadian telephone equipment manufacturer in
which BT took a controlling 51 per cent stake in 1985.
However, the central plank of BT's international strategy remains its
ambitious plans to provide global telecommunications services to
multinational companies.
As part of this strategy BT established Syncordia, an Atlanta, Georgia-based
network management company, which operates GNS, a data communications
company, and has developed a plan dubbed Operation Cyclone to invest Dollars
1bn over the next decade in infrastructure outside the UK.
A link with EDS might provide Syncordia with more credibility and access to
business cus-tomers.
For GM, an investment in EDS by an outside party would mean a useful
injection of cash when the motor company has been financially stretched by
two years of severe losses. However, GM has said in the past that EDS, one
of its more profitable businesses, is not for sale outright.
For EDS itself, an outside partner in the telecommunications field might
help its penetration of international markets, though it already has a
sophisticated international telecommunications network of its own.
A new equity stakeholder could also give its management additional freedom
from GM's embrace. Relations between GM and EDS were volatile in the early
years, as the cultures of the two companies clashed, but analysts say they
are now much better.
EDS, estimated to be the world's largest provider of computer services, has
enjoyed rapid growth in recent years which has sharply reduced its
dependence on GM for revenues.
It still handled most of GM's computer operations, but its non-GM revenues
could reach 70 per cent of the total by 1995, compared to just 29 per cent
in 1985.
Its business involves systems integration - designing computer networks -
and 'outsourcing' of data processing, which means managing clients' entire
computer operations.
</TEXT>
