<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JAN 93 / International Company News: Rhone-Poulenc share sale is
over-subscribed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE French government announced last night that the sale of shares in
Rhone-Poulenc, the flagship French chemicals company, had been healthily
over-subscribed.
The sale, which forms part of the socialist administration's partial
privatisation programme, involved the sale of 6m shares at FFr500 (Dollars
94) each.
The finance ministry said last night that demand from French investors had
been so strong that part of the 255,000 shares originally allocated for
foreign investors would be transfered to France.
Originally the French government had intended to stage the Rhone-Poulenc
share sale late last year.
However, the sale was postponed because of the precarious state of the Paris
stock market, then very volatile in the wake of a series of money market
attacks on the French franc.
Rhone-Poulenc is one of a number of France's state-controlled companies to
be involved in the partial privatisation programme which is expected to
accelerate if, as the opinion polls suggest, the right returns to power
after the French legislative elections in March.
